# Command gource

## What does this command do:

Software projects are displayed by Gource as an animated tree with the root directory of the project at its centre. Directories appear as branches with files as leaves. Developers can be seen working on the tree at the times they contributed to the project.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `sudo dnf install gource`
For Raspberry Pi install using: `sudo apt install gource`
For Mac install using: `brew install gource`

## Command path

For Fedora run: `/usr/bin/gource`
For Raspberry Pi run: `/usr/bin/gource`
For Mac run: `/usr/bin/gource`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://gource.io/

## Command options

# Basic usage
gource                          # Animate git log from current directory
gource /path/to/repo            # Animate git log from specified path
gource logfile.txt              # Animate from a pre-generated log file

# Display
gource -WIDTHxHEIGHT            # Set viewport size (e.g. -1280x720)
gource -f                       # Fullscreen
gource --screen SCREEN          # Screen number
gource --high-dpi               # Request a high DPI display

# Playback control
gource --start-date 'YYYY-MM-DD hh:mm:ss +tz'  # Start at a date
gource --stop-date  'YYYY-MM-DD hh:mm:ss +tz'  # Stop at a date
gource -p 0.5                   # Start at position (0.0-1.0 or 'random')
gource --stop-at-end            # Stop at end of the log
gource --loop                   # Loop at the end of the log
gource -s 1                     # Speed: seconds per day (default: 10)
gource --realtime               # Realtime playback speed
gource -c 2.0                   # Time scale multiplier (default: 1.0)
gource -a 1                     # Auto-skip if idle for N seconds (default: 3)

# Camera
gource --camera-mode track      # Camera mode: overview or track
gource --padding 1.2            # Camera padding (default: 1.1)
gource --disable-auto-rotate    # Disable automatic camera rotation
gource --follow-user "Alice"    # Camera follows this user

# Users and files
gource --user-scale 1.5         # Scale user avatars (default: 1.0)
gource --user-image-dir ./avatars  # Dir with avatar images
gource --default-user-image img.png  # Fallback avatar image
gource --colour-images          # Colourize user images
gource --user-filter REGEX      # Ignore usernames matching regex
gource --file-filter REGEX      # Ignore file paths matching regex
gource --max-files 0            # Max files shown (0 = no limit)

# Appearance
gource -b 000000                # Background colour in hex (default: 000000)
gource --background-image bg.png  # Set a background image
gource --title "My Project"     # Set a title
gource --key                    # Show file extension key
gource --hide users,filenames   # Hide display elements:
                                # bloom,date,dirnames,files,filenames,
                                # mouse,progress,root,tree,users,usernames
gource --highlight-users        # Highlight names of all users
gource --highlight-dirs         # Highlight names of all directories
gource --font-size 18           # Font size for date and title
gource --font-colour FFFFFF     # Font colour in hex

# Output (for recording)
gource -o output.ppm            # Output PPM stream to file ('-' for STDOUT)
gource -r 60                    # Output framerate (25, 30, 60)

# Pipe to ffmpeg for MP4
gource -1280x720 -s 1 -o - | ffmpeg -y -r 60 -f image2pipe -vcodec ppm -i - -vcodec libx264 -preset ultrafast -pix_fmt yuv420p output.mp4

# Log generation
gource --log-command git        # Show the VCS log command used
gource --output-custom-log custom.log  # Output custom format log

# Git-specific
gource --git-branch main        # Visualize a specific git branch

# Config
gource --save-config my.conf    # Save current options to config file
gource --load-config my.conf    # Load options from config file
